text: THEORY TIME! I don't see the  daughter in the funeral scene, only the service in church. I think she dies and it's her burial, not the grandma's. I think people are glossing over the two shots of the brother and sister in the car, then the miniature model of that same shot, except of the daughter hanging out of the window of the car. Seems curious to me that the mom would make that into a miniature model. There is also a sound effect of a car speeding, and the glares at the end look like the reflection of a car's headlights. I think these things have more to do with the story than is being let on. I have a feeling the girl is/was special and the brother had something to do with her dying and he's being haunted by the grandma. Not sure what this has to do with hereditary traits, but it's fun to guess! Can't wait to see it! üòä

text: The sound design of this trailer alone is fantastic. First we have the mouth clicking sound, which is added into the cuts at mixed intervals to create an alien, uneasy feeling. The fluttering sound is introduced early in the trailer, then reapplied to the bird before it hits the window. She is about to cut off the bird head before we hear a crackling, which initially we perceive as the sound of the bird's neck being crushed but then it is revealed to be a match being lit, all in a fraction of a second. The random plucking of strings in the soundtrack is just really creepy. The binaural bell sound is weird as heck. The banging sound is introduced a couple shots before we find the source of it, which is first revealed as a knife against a cutting board but is then translated into her banging her head against the floor. We see a woman scream and think the ringing sound playing at the same time is the sound of her scream, but as it lingers we realize it is just a ringing. Every cut has a noise or combination of noises to bridge it over to the next moment.

text: This movie looks off-the-charts terrifying, and I cannot wait to see it. I'm a lifelong horror fan, I write horror films, I watch them every day, and have been since before kindergarten. And Hereditary looks like a true game-changer of sorts. When I first saw this trailer, it legit gave me the chills. What frightens me most about it is how little I know. Everything is so ambiguous. I get that Annie Graham (Collette) lost her mother, and that's where it all starts. But I cannot make out or predict ANYTHING else. So I am itching like crazy to see this in theatres. Toni Collette is an amazing actress who seems to be at the top of her game playing a grieving daughter who's somehow sinking into insanity. Debut actress Milly Shapiro is SO creepy-looking, I'm sure she's gonna be the next great addition to the "creepy kids" horror clich√© (I mean it in a good way). The bugs crawling on Peter's face in bed, Annie smashing her head against that wall, all those weird cult members swarming about, and Toni Collette's seemingly bone-chilling performance is what makes this movie look so different from standard genre fare. Looking forward to calling it my latest favorite horror flick.

Then it shows someone trying to rip his head off, and later bugs crawling all over his head. Also the mom makes a miniature of the son without a head, so... I think that the whole family will die, starting with the daughter then the father then the son and the mother. The reason I think this will happen is because the daughter obviously dies first because of the shot of the funeral. Then the dad dies, leaving only the mother and the son, which in a trailer with cast interviews, one of the actors, I don‚Äôt remember which, said they didnt have a very good relationship. I‚Äôm not sure how the mother will die, but I think it has something to do with her(possibly) floating up into the treehouse. I‚Äôm not sure what will happen, but since the daughter was decapitated, maybe the mom will get cut up into little pieces or something because she makes the figurines. Just a theory.

text: Rating 2/5:  Just watched it. Semi-decent horror film with reviews blown out of proportion. For 99% of the film, it's a very familiar horror film of a family suffering from loss of a family member and trying to figure out if something's haunting their family. And then boom -- in the ending we're thrown some weird pagan stuff - where everything that had been built up until that point, including a pretty convincing family drama, just blew up - and nothing made sense in the end.  It's almost as if the screenwriter/director decided to make this a different horror film by adding some angles in the end. But it completely ruined what would have been a pretty decent horror film. I think I heard people laughing and shaking their heads at the ending; I certainly did. Writing is a very difficult art - and every story is a promise. Unfortunately, that promise was not fulfilled in this film -- and none of the characters resolved.  The writer/director is inexperienced this being his first film, and it showed in the ending.
author: Sid Katragadda

text: Went and watched this yesterday and it was awful!!! Don't waste your money as it's around 30 minutes of content stretched over 2hrs 10mins (roughly). There are a couple of uneasy moments but apart from those it is terrible. The ending is ridiculously bad and a lot of the film made no sense whatsoever. The movie is shot very well by the director but even with that it still doesn't make up for the lack of substance. Numerous long winded scenes of suspense all ended by absolutely nothing whatsoever... it's almost as if they used it as a filler to pad the movie out. Of all the people on the cinema not one single person left saying anything positive whatsoever about it... quite the opposite actually. A lot of people left disgruntled and tired due to it being incredibly boring and a story that doesn't make sense really. Even if I had of rented this movie once it went on Xbox live, and even if it cost ¬£2 to rent... I would still feel as if I had of been ripped off. I implore you to not waste your money or time by watching this movie. I love all forms of horror films so am not only saying this as someone who doesn't like or understand films like this... it's just Hereditary is *THAT* bad. Giving you my honest rating I couldn't give it any more than 3/10 and that's giving it that high of a score due to the way it was shot and the music... but the characters and movie it's self don't even warrant a score from me. Overall: TERRIBLE MOVIE, ANNOYING CAST & A WASTE OF 2HRS OF YOUR LIFE.

text: Went to see this last night, just to kill time after work. Had no idea what it was about, hadn't seen the trailer. Barely read a synopsis. Especially if you consider yourself a horror film buff (like myself). Because the director constantly throws out clues that any long time horror fan will pick up on immediately. text: Shite film in my opinion. You know it‚Äôs bad when people start to uncontrollably laugh throughout the film because it makes absolutely no sense. As well as this the trailer over glorifies the it! I‚Äôd prefer to take a shit in my hands and clap than waste another 2 hours of my life watching this train wreck of a horror! The critics have obviously been paid or forced to make good reviews to attract an audience. Here‚Äôs my honest ratings for this film: 1/10 for story as nothing actually made sense. 4/10 for the editing as the only actually scary part was a bird hitting a window! 5/10 for the props. 4/10 for the acting although i didn‚Äôt feel a connection or understanding with the characters as we were shown no background on what built them till further into the film. 2/10 for events in the story as it is a stereotypical horror film, e.g. someone dies, strange events, deaths, long build up of suspense and tension and then a terrible ending which no one actually understood until they got home and watch a video on explaining the ending and all the secret meanings. Looking at other unprofessional and amateur reviewers ideas on this film are much better for example on person said ‚ÄúWhat a shocking film, was it meant to be funny‚Äù others said that the film is diabolical, a waste of money, no context behind the daughters clucks/clicks, people asking why there were naked dead bodies which some of them were decapitated and old were shown in a film rated 15. To be impartial Jeffery M. Anderson wrote saying ‚ÄúThis clammy, creeping horror film is deeply rooted to the classics from the 1960s, ‚Äò70s and beyond‚Äù This reviewer gave the film a 8/10. Overall i give this film a horrifying 3.2/10 making this rated lower than Winchester (2018), Leprechaun Origins (2014), The Ouija Experiment (2013) and even Killer Tomatoes Strike Back! If you want to watch a real horror, try watching the Insidious trilogy and The Conjuring films! Audiences beware of this film, it will waste two hours of your time and it will ruin your evening. Thank you for reading this, I‚Äôd highly recommend that everyone stays far away from this ‚Äòhorror‚Äô.

text: *Spoiler free comment*  I love the horror genre, but too often people recommended "horror" movies, telling me: Dude, watch this one, it's really scary! But the only thing scary was being afraid of cheap jumpscares only brought to you by sudden extremly loud music for 120 minutes. To me, that is NOT horror!  I'm used to gore and creepy stuff, but this movie is the second one I've watched in my life I would actually call macabre. Never before have I wished for a movie to finally end while sitting in the cinema, unable to pause - but not because it was bad, quite the contrary: it was amazing! It gave me a constant unpleasant feeling which became almost unbearable at some point.  And guess what? 127 minutes without a single jumpscare!  If anyone will ask me from now on: 'how do you define horror?' I'd tell them: 'Watch Hereditary. Nuff said"  Best horror movie I've ever seen

text: I enjoy a smart horror flick without the cliche's of jumpscares and cheesy teen actors however to enjoy this movie your imagination will be working overtime. So much backstory left unfinished and explained away with a grandmother that kept secrets. The first hour and approximately 10 mins is more depressing than scary. Without stating the spoilers it does have some creepy scenes that could have been explored more but the ending was sloppily, hastily and even far fetched all the while considering it's a movie containing the paranormal. Reviewers please stop comparing it to The Exorcist. We don't need another Exorcist anyhow. Let's face it, the creepyness is mainly due to the strange appearance of the little girl. This movie is more like Bad Ben with a bigger buget, poltergeist with a weaker script, The Shining with decapitation or The Witch + Insidious have a baby. This film could've had so much potential. I could think of plenty of ways that the second half could've gone and would've been more plausible, enjoyable and actually scary. But instead we are left with a Night M. Shamallama after his first 3 films. Highlights of the film are the mother's acting ability and the camera work.

text: I so badly want to say that I loved it and it was worth all the praise, but it would feel wrong to say that. I really wanted to like this movie going in. Honestly though, it isn't the holy grail of horror movies, it isn't a modern horror classic. I love horror movies and have seen so many of them since I were a little child. I have also seen fair share of disturbing, provoking and chilling movies and those that make you feel nauseous and like you want to throw up. This movie wasn't "too disgusting for me" and it didn't go over my head. The problem is just that it's honestly just a letdown. It spends a lot of time establishing key elements, the atmosphere, building expectations and suspense, but when it comes to perfecting them and finally reaching the climax, it falls flat. At points it feels like you're not knowing what you should really be afraid of. The film seems to juggle different elements and plots without fully developing them and then expecting the audience to get everything. There were honestly many scenes that still seem like stuff that should have maybe been left out. When your audience is confused and even laughs at the theater (yes, there were people genuinely howling from laughter, not just using it as a coping mechanism), you know you have failed to really get the point across.   I love the fact that it didn't focus on cheap jumpscares and that it carefully molded expectations and reached to the human psyche. The acting was spot on, I absolutely adore the symbolism, foreshadowings, classic horror elements and the whole atmosphere of the movie. It had the technicalities right and the art side right. It was really ambitious and well done and beats so many modern horror movies, but the hype and praise kind of ruin it honestly. If I would have seen this blindly I would have been more pleasantly surprised of it. Of course, that still wouldn't have made the movie more clearer. This movie would have needed serious polishing and by so many little tweaks it would have been better. This movie had what it takes to be a classic, but it' leans toward being that typical cult horror movie. It's sad to see so much good things not carry on to their full potential.

text: This is maybe the best horror movie I have seen in the last 5 years, maybe more. No cheap horror, 0 jumpscares. Scenery direction that reminds that of Hichcock's, motion capture and sound capable of giving you chills down your spine, and the plot... All I can say is that the guys who wrote the scenario have done their homework. Some crucial parts of the plot require some knowledge on certain subjects. The absence of jumpscares along with the specific pieces of knowledge required are the main reasons most of the people I know who have watched it said - to my surprise - that it's crap and a waste of money. I hope the horror genre gives us more similar works such as this masterpiece, instead of cheap jumpscare trash with boogeymen whose only horror is their makeup. I understood and enjoyed every second of it, and if you are like me, you are going to love the movie.

text: Spoiler-Free Review   I hardly ever write reviews but after seeing this movie I really felt the need to write a long one.   Reading all these reviews about what a "Masterpiece" this movie is makes me wonder if I missed something or if I'm just stupid. If you're someone who's raving about how creative and legendary this movie is, you're either just trying to fit in as a horror movie person or saw a completely different movie. Seriously, I sat there through the first hour of the movie and wondered if I somehow walked into the wrong theater and was seeing a different movie. The first half of the movie just seemed to keep me waiting and waiting and waiting for something sensible to happen.   The only positive thing about this movie is the acting. The movie does have good performances from Toni Collette, although I don't feel her acting is "Oscar worthy" like people are saying.   In the end, there's nothing to spoil about this movie because nothing happens. The plot develops extremely slowly as a poorly written family drama. Then in the last 20-30 minutes the director must have remembered that he was supposed to be making a horror movie and just slapped together an ending full of countless scary movie cliches that left everyone in the theater scratching their heads. My instant reaction after the movie ended was ‚ÄúWhat did I just watch‚Äù   I get that cinematography wise this movie is supposed to be brilliant, because it does look pretty good. But good visuals aren't enough to save a boring movie with a poorly put together plot in my opinion. I've seen a few other reviewers on here mention how people in the audience were laughing out loud during the "scary" parts of this movie, and I can say that most of the theater I was in, including myself, was filled with people laughing and making jokes at how confusing the ending of this movie is.   DO NOT WASTE YOUR MONEY IF YOU ARE PLANNING TO WATCH IT IN THE CINEMA. You may want to see it at home if you like because there‚Äôs nothing special about it that‚Äôll give u chills in the movie theatre. I‚Äôm so sick of artsy type ‚Äúhorror movies‚Äù. Don‚Äôt tell me ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt get it‚Äù. I got it and it was stupid.   5/10 ( Just because of the good acting )

text: good movie. the reason why it's not great is because of the ending, but we'll get to that in a minute. so typically I feel that horror movies in general just aren't very good. they are all very predictable, they are all very similar and to be honest most of them just kind of make me laugh when they start adding those cgi monsters and very predictable jump scares. horror movies are always fun, but they're never really good movies. this one was different for me, it was incredible in so many ways. i've never felt so fucking disturbed and just uncomfortable watching a movie before. it just set this extremely eerie tone like i've never seen before in a horror film. it left me thinking like "what if it were me in this situation?" and it genuinely made me super uncomfortable. this was the first movie in which i've actually had nightmares after i've watched it, and it was fucking awesome. the movie was just absolutely disgusting, in an amazing way. however, the very sad part which pissed me off was the ending. guys, you're better off walking out of the theatre 10-15 mins before the movie ends if you don't want to get extremely disappointed. the ending is just surreal. it felt like a joke tbh lmao they started adding unnecessary cgi and the movie just turned into a circus act pretty much. i watched it with my girlfriend at the cinema and she felt sick during the entire movie, when the ending came even she started laughing and was like "you know what, this movie isn't so bad after all". what a joke LOL but as for the rest of the movie, fucking A+, it's disturbing. not a movie for everyone taste, that's for sure

text: I can't praise this film enough. This is what horror films should strive to be. Original storyline (i.e., not a sequel/reboot/remake), stellar acting (particularly from Collette), excellent cinematography, brilliant music, neither too short nor too long, an unpredictable plot, and a focus on lingering, pervasive dread and terror instead of an over-reliance on cheap jumpscares. This may well be my favourite horror film, and generally I'm very hard to impress. I can't wait to see what Aster does next.

text: As many others, I loved this movie and I think it's one of the best horror movies of recent times, no cheap scares, an actual coherent story that can be seen as completely grounded and real up until the last third of it. Only thing I want to point out is that it's okay to not like the movie, it might not be your thing, for however reason, if you enjoy more jump scary common ones or slasher horror movies, whatever. Two things I don't think are okay: First, showing up to say "This movie sucks. I want my money back" like a dumb kid who didn't like the food they ordered at a restaurant, it helps in no way and makes you look like an idiot. Want to give your piece of criticism and why you didn't like it? Perfectly fine, do it like an adult. Second, people who liked the movie and immediatly put down anyone who didn't as "your IQ must be low, you didn't get it", probably just as stupid as hating with no argument to back it up, you make people who enjoyed the movie look like snobs with no real reasons as to why they enjoyed it, also doesn't help in the conversation at all and you will never convince anyone to give the movie you liked another try or a second viewing just by insulting them. Just my two cents about what I've seen the most in the comments.

text: A lot of people are saying they didn't like the film.  The only problem is they're most likely used to the horror movies coming out with jump scares like the Annabelle and Insidious movies, but this is a movie that really sticks with you.  Movies like the new It with jump scares are fun to watch and laugh after you jump, but if you're laughing at this movie...I don't even know how anyone could do such a thing.  Maybe if they're uncomfortable and anxious, but if they're genuinely laughing at it because they think it's funny, then they obviously don't know effective horror.  This movie was phenomenal.  I loved the acting, the writing, just everything about it made me feel uncomfortable in the best way.  And the score was great.  It matched the movie perfectly.  Nowadays, instead of relying on great acting and great writing and great scores like this movie has, people are relying on jump scares and CGI monsters.  This is a movie with the full package.  I will  be honest, obviously it's imperfect, but compared to horror movies nowadays, this is perfection.

text: Stupid movie, even though it has great acting, a great scary vibe and great cinematography. It had a lot of promise at the start but in the end it just became total utter senseless BULLSHIT! Somehow the audience is supposed to believe that there is a cult who have been trying to summon this demon Paimon for generations and finally they acheive this through a series of serendipetous coincidences and bizzare activities that seem totally absurd, illogical and unnecessary. I mean If this demon Paimon needed a male host why didn't that Joan character just kidnap the boy, kill him and then let the demon take his body. Oh the demon needs three decapitated heads? Then why didn't Joan or the Grandmother just decapitate three people and use their heads and bodies in the ritual. Somehow the audience is supposed to believe that Joan and the grandmother conspired with this demon Paimon to get him into the body of grandson (Peter), even to the extent that we have to assume that Paimon and Joan got together to come up with the brilliant plan to set up a fake seance reaction to convince the mother (Annie) that Joan was able to summon the spirit of her "dead grandson" Louis. I mean WTF?  Once again this demonstrate the absurdity and utter lack of imagination of the  writers. Such convoluted nonsense! It detracted from the brilliant acting performance from Toni Colelette.

author: Ritchel Ritch

text: I've been so anxious to see this film and was thrilled to find a 4k copy on the shelf early a couple of days ago.  Whoa.  Not many films make me genuinely uneasy, but this one definitely did.  There have been some pretty highly critically acclaimed scary movies in the last few years, and as much as I loved "The Witch", "It Follows", "The Babadook", "It Comes At Night" and "A Quiet Place".....none of these chilled me half as much as "Hereditary". The entire cast is perfection but Toni Collette is astonishing, not surprised, but she can go really deep and heavy, it would be difficult to comprehend if she wasn't nominated for an Oscar for this performance.  And I think Alex Wolff's performance helped pull the thing off...he's brilliant.   "Hereditary" sits comfortable next to "The Shining", "The Wicker Man", "Rosemary's Baby", "The Thing", "The Witch" and a few of my other favorite horror films....thinking back on those after seeing this one, they don't seem quite as scary? I gotta get in a couple more viewings in the next months to be sure, but it just might end up being my favorite horror film of all time.  It almost made me feel like I needed to go to church Sunday morning....it's still rattling around in my mind.  If you just like mindless jump scare stuff it might not be for you, but if you want to see a real horror film...don't miss it.  EPIC HORROR. End of story. :-)

text: Ari Aster is talented, but I don't think he's quite hit his stride just yet. Hereditary has an excellent first half, with strong performances and an ominous mood that's helped in no small part by the droning score that's played throughout virtually the entire film. But things start to unravel in the second half. Don't get me wrong, I respect any film that TRIES to do something different these days. It's a rare thing, indeed. But without giving anything away, while the story was wildly unpredictable towards the end, it didn't end up as something I found particularly interesting. And there was also this very forced juxtaposition between Toni Collette's unhinged and hysterical overacting (good but extreme) and the rest of the cast, which was as stiff and wooden as the little dolls in Toni's doll houses. But the worst part for me was how the film just tried too hard to be strange and different. If you want to be strange and different, you'd better make sure that the story you're telling is compelling enough to support all the camera trickery, weird angles and artificial shots. And I just don't think the story was good enough to do that.  This was like watching something by David Lynch, but without his masterful style and genuine feel for the bizarre. It felt as if I was watching a big budget student film, with way better performances than it deserved.  I'm still looking forward to seeing what Ari can come up with in the future. But so far, while he's taken a step in the right direction, he's got neither a map or a compass to follow yet.

text: LOL. A mediocre movie. People are just not too familiar with a slower editing style, long-takes, wide angle shots, etc. Not surprising, considering the junk they typically watch. They've mistook halfway decent pacing with immersion and craft. In fact, some of the camera moves were clumsy and often without "motivation" in the action. This film was simply a dime-a-dozen demon flick. I hope the success of the film will encourage some directors to change editing styles, but that's about all this forgettable movie can contribute to 2018. A similar recent movie, "It Follows", was a bit  better. It didn't rely on gore and silly demonic physics. However, if a movie is made in the 2000s or twenty-teens, you can be fairly sure it's garbage. If people found the style of the film refreshing, I suggest they return to the Classics.

text: I can think of four reasons a person wouldn't like this movie. The first is exposure, it's best to go in knowing nothing, massive expectations will have you enter the theatre with a critical mind and leave you disappointed. It is pretty impossible for a movie to be the scariest movie ever for everyone, given different things scare different people and the experience is entirely subjective. So get that catch phrase out of your head and expect nothing. The second is where you get your kicks, I find jumpscares to be a reflex, like the knee jerk reaction. If you're very physically focused then this is probably all it takes to satisfy your horror needs, and If that's the case Hereditary might be a big yawn fest for you. The third is whether you are an empathic person, much of the horror is delivered via empathy with the characters, if you don't empathise naturally then it'll go right over your head. And the fourth is just not liking/tolerating horror and disturbing content, but it's unlikely you're watching heredity if that's the case. I'd say there are good indicators of whether you'll like this based on what you've liked before,  if you liked scream and hostel, this'll probably be terrible to you, if you like nordic noir and artsy indie movies about horrible things happening in terrible places, you might like this. I've watched tons of horror(including foreign) and honestly I've never seen anything like it, and for me that was a good thing. It's in my top two most memorable movies of any genre. (second place to incendies which is perfection imo). A definite standout.

text: I feel like those people who don't get why this movie is one of the scariest and best horror movies of modern cinema aren't at the same level of wavelength as those who get it. The eerie, dreadful, uneasiness, and depressing depictions throughout the whole movie was something I havent seen in a LONG time. Not one point of the movie was there any sense of happiness. Nothing but guilt. Scenes were disturbing: from the sounds in the backround to the strange movements of the characters. Not only that, the reactions of each character to their inexplicable and terrifying environment was so realistic. For example, the still shot of Peter sitting in his car after the accident, too tramautized to move, was incredible. The slow pans, the still and silent shots, the amazing cinematography of this film was perfect and captured the moments in the best way. 10/10.

text: For a horror this was pretty good, but not sure why people were so impressed. Still not scary!  Annie frustrated the crap out of me. It's one thing to believe in something that others will obviously find crazy, its another thing to perfectly portray a crazy person when trying to deliver the truth to them. "PLEASE, PLEASE, PLEASE, JUST FOLLOW ME" (she says while stroking their arm and clinging on to them in a desperate way). I mean... the story-truth was crazy... but she managed to deliver it in a way to make sure no one believed her! I can't stand people who can't keep themselves together.  If reality throws something at you that's crazy from your perspective... all that means is that reality wasn't what you thought it was. You say 'yes', and continue from your new perspective. All this - 'this can't be' - bullshit in movies drives me nuts. It is the very definition of a limited mind! If this is an accurate portrayal of a human being, then thats scarier to me than this movie.

text: This is a really great movie. The story is really engaging and emotional. The film is well directed and well shot. The characters are complex and are easy to get invested into and the actors do a fantastic job of giving out some great performances.  Although If l had to pick who gave the best performance in the movie, it would be Milly Shapiro as Charlie Graham. She did such a great job of making her character feel creepy. Every time she came on screen, I felt uncomfortable.  If I had any complaints about this film, is that the pacing can be really slow at times, but the payoff at the end of the film makes up for the slow pacing.  I absolutely love this movie. It's a film that I've been thinking a lot about ever since I first watched it. I'm sure there's a lot of hidden details about this film when I first watched it and I can't wait to watch it again to see if I discover any new things that I didn't see when I first watched it.  I think it's a film that years from now, we'll be looking at as a horror classic. It's up there with Don't Breathe and Get Out as one of the best horror films of the 2010s in my opinion .  If I had to give this film a rating, I would give it a eight out of ten.

text: Spoiler-free    If you get scared easily or you have a weak heart,  *don't even consider watching this*  it will haunt you for eternity and will scar you for LIFE! ( I did that mistake) I watched it and I can't get any sleep. If I was lucky enough to have some sleep, It would be nightmares.  And I'm not the only one. Almost everyone became hysterically ill after watching this film. It's extremely extremely disturbing. I have watched films of the same horror genre like Mother!, Get Out, The Witch; films that have this peculiar eerie vibe and films that affect you on many levels and is especially disturbing . Horror film fanatics will love this film. If you haven't been scared by any horror film then I assure you this one is like no other. If it will not scare you then it will definitely disturb you for a long time. It is really terrifying and the imagery is terrifyingly violent and is still stuck in my mind and the music makes it even worse. I find it to be honest very impressive yet unsettling how it's the debut film for Ari Aster, the director and writer. You can't be normal to write and direct such film and at such a young age (not too young, 30/31, but still). Overall it's an exceptional film yet I don't recommend it for anyone. I would recommend reading the synopsis about the film or have an idea about it. It will help you prepare mentally. It would be more disturbing to watch it without knowing a thing about it.     An advice don't read about the film after watching it. It will disturb you even further.

text: I like to consider myself a tough guy... More than most anyways. Been to war a few times, had a knife held to my throat as a child, locked in the basement for days by my stepmother.. molested by babysitters and my step mother, got lost in a foreign third world country and walked back to civilization for 13 hours in the dark by myself. Gotten over everything with only a few bad memories.  But watching this movie on a sunny day with my girlfriend and dog on the bed was too much. It's been 7 hours and they're both asleep, I'm still shaken from this disgusting piece of art. A foreboding sense is looming over me and I feel like I'm waiting for something bad to happen. As if this movie just cursed me and all of my luck was used up surviving my past traumas. Hereditary may be what ends me. I am afraid for once and I wanted to document what may be my last hour.

text: This movie scared, freak me out and disturbed me so badly I have to rate it one of the best horror movies in spite of a stupid part at the end.  I felt uneasy, scary and disturbed for weeks after I watched it I just couldn't get it out of my head.  The first time I watched it I said never again, but that next morning, my tv cut itself on, loaded the movie back up on my KODI app on the firestick and started playing itself again to my amazement and horror I woke up to the sound of the scary music and I new exactly what I would see when I turned over...I was like "WTF???" ***Spoiler***        ***Spoiler*** The problem I had with the ending This movie would get 5 stars if it weren't for the part where the possessed mom teleports in the attic and manages to saw her own head completely off with piano wire then levitates into the tree house.  What would have been SO MUCH BETTER and SCARIER would have been if her occult followers had cut her head off and taken her decapitated bleeding body up into the tree house as blood sacrifice.  People since the dawn of man have done horrific murders in the name of religion and belief in a deity that requires decapitated heads and the willingness to provide them as tithes is some scary shit.  Still I have to give the movie a strong rating because everything up to that point had me on the edge of my seat with a WTF look on my face and staring at the corners of my ceilings in the dark for weeks.

text: I just watched this at close to 11 at night, and I checked the percentage on my phone battery and saw it was at 1%. Without thinking I quickly unplugged my lamp to plug in my charger and I was instantly terrified of the dark. I was starting to breathe heavily and it felt like someone was walking towards me until I turned on the flashlight on my phone and was able to plug my lamp back in. I sat there for a few minutes catching my breath and then kept watching without headphones and at a lower volume. Ive havent been scared of the dark since I was like 10 years old, but watching Annie banging her head against the attic, hiding on the ceiling, going to the treehouse, and imagining myself in peters shoes, seeing everything happen to him was absolutely terrifying. I don‚Äôt believe in god too much, but this all seemed so utterly horrific that I tried praying for the first time in forever. This movie made me feel unpure and I‚Äôm scared of every noise in my house at 12:44 at night now. 11/10 I‚Äôm gonna struggle with sleeping in the dark for a while, go give it a watch if you haven‚Äôt.

text: I am highly shook after watching this movie. The storytelling could have been improved (it's kind of hard to enjoy the final gag when there's confusion afoot) and there could have been more scares (but the ones that did happen were totally unique). This movie was a devastatingly forward looking take on the same old story, but you will literally enjoy it more the second time you watch it because then you actually know what's going on. This was the directorial debut of a writer, and it probably shouldn't have been. He should've waited five years before writing/directing this because it needed refining. It's really a quite simple story-there is no need for the audience to be confused and have to go on Wikipedia just to figure out what actually happened in the end. It could've been a masterpiece if the writer/director had more experience under his belt but the unrefined final product was still ultimately fantastic. Should've been a home run with all audiences. Instead it's a gag for those who have the patience to sit through two hours of borderline hogwash to get to the best part- the reveal.

text: I not only rate Hereditary 5 Stars or Two Thumbs Up or Whatever-However they do it these days. When it comes to a movie's genre being Horror Mystery Thriller Drama all wrapped up in one, as far as I'm concerned, this movie will equate correspondingly in the annals of time with such classics as The Exorcist, The Omen, and Alien! And, whew, as for Toni Collette? She's just above and beyond all and the consummate actress of today on so many levels. The word 'superlative' comes to mind, no matter what movie part I've seen her play or do.  The best compliment I can conceivably come up with to pay Toni Collette is as this here:  Even though the two ladies were two different actresses from two different times in life; if anyone would be deserving of a  "Bette Davis Award" trophy (vs the fictitious Sara Siddons Award in her 1950 movie All About Eve), if there were such an award given today (and there should be by now!), it would go to Toni Collette hands down!  That's the best compliment I could come up with for Toni Colette.  She's just GOOD!               üòéüèÜüòÅ Ps ... Everyone else was good in it too.           üòä
